Article: 6\
News_Outlet: CNN\
Title: How outlawing abortion could worsen America\'92s maternal mortality crisis\
Author: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/profiles/priya-krishnakumar"}}{\fldrslt \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Priya Krishnakumar}}\AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  and Daniel Wolfe\
\AppleTypeServices Publication_Date: \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Updated 11:58 AM EDT, Fri June 24, 2022\AppleTypeServices \
Article_Content: CNN \'a0\'97\'a0\AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Dr. Judette Louis recalls a time when she treated a patient who was hemorrhaging from her pregnancy \'97 and how she had to wait to obtain permission before she was allowed to terminate the pregnancy for the health of the mother. \'93I was standing there watching her hemorrhage out, waiting for permission to do the termination. It is a disgusting feeling. It is a sad feeling. And you\'92re sitting there literally watching her blood pressure going down while you\'92re waiting for permission,\'94 the Chair of Obstetrics and Gynecology at the University of South Florida told CNN. \'93It\'92s just sad to now know \'85 that that will be happening all over across the country where [terminating a pregnancy] won\'92t even be a possibility for a lot of states.\'94 Dr. Louis and other health care experts fear that with Roe v. Wade overturned, potential widespread abortion bans will deepen the United States\'92 maternal mortality crisis.
\f1 \AppleTypeServices \uc0\u8239 
\f0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539  Health care experts told CNN they worry that reducing access to abortion \'97 by closing clinics, setting early gestational limits or outlawing the procedure altogether \'97 may lead to more pregnancy-related deaths in the United States. Rates of pregnancy-related deaths in the US are the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.commonwealthfund.org/publications/issue-briefs/2020/nov/maternal-mortality-maternity-care-us-compared-10-countries"}}{\fldrslt highest in the developed world}} and have risen steadily over time, with Black women three times more likely to die in pregnancy or childbirth than White women. The CDC recently reported that the rate of pregnancy-related deaths increased from 20.1 in 2019 to 23.8 in 2020, continuing a worrying trend of worsening maternal health outcomes for people in the United States. Now that the Supreme Court has overturned Roe v. Wade, 26 states are poised to ban abortion through pre-existing bans or {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/05/03/us/state-abortion-trigger-laws-roe-v-wade-overturned/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \'93trigger laws\'94}} that will now go into effect without the landmark ruling is no longer in place. As a result, more than 10 million people of reproductive age would have to cross state lines to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2021/10/30/politics/roe-wade-reversal-abortion-driving-distances/index.html"}}{\fldrslt access the procedure}} in the nearest state where it is legal, according to the Guttmacher Institute, a research and policy institute that supports legal abortion rights. \'93[People] may seek unsafe ways of terminating a pregnancy and could have harmful consequences,\'94 said Whitney Rice, the director of the Center for Reproductive Health Research in the Southeast at Emory University. \'93You also have people who may sort of be forced to continue pregnancies to term and could have a risk of infant health outcomes that include low birth weight, preterm birth, or may have a risk of maternal mortality.\'94 Maternal mortality rates are already high in those states {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.guttmacher.org/article/2021/10/26-states-are-certain-or-likely-ban-abortion-without-roe-heres-which-ones-and-why"}}{\fldrslt certain or likely}} to ban abortion \'97 47% higher than the national rate, according to a CNN analysis of 2018 data from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the most recent available. \AppleTypeServices Maternal mortality rates are higher in states likely to ban abortion In 2018 maternal mortality rates were, on average, 47% higher than the national rate in states the Guttmacher Institute says are certain or likely to ban abortion with Roe v. Wade now overturned. \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Overall, states with the most restrictive abortion laws had a 7% higher maternal mortality rate than states with fewer restrictions, according to a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://ajph.aphapublications.org/doi/full/10.2105/AJPH.2021.306396"}}{\fldrslt 2021 study }}in the American Journal of Public Health. States that restricted abortion based on gestational limits saw a steep rise in the maternal mortality rate by 38%, according to a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0749379719304192"}}{\fldrslt 2020 study in the American Journal of Preventive Medicine}}. A 20% reduction in Planned Parenthood clinics in a state between 2007-2015 resulted, on average, in an increase in the state\'92s maternal mortality rates by 8%. \AppleTypeServices Study: Restricting access to abortion led to increases in mortality rates In the 18 states where Planned Parenthood clinics decreased by 20%, maternal mortality rates increased by 8%. Rates in the 12 states where abortions were restricted by gestational age increased by 38%, according to a 2020 study in the American Journal of Preventative Medicine. Maternal mortality risks are felt unequally \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Black people are three times more likely to die of pregnancy-related causes than non-Hispanic White and Hispanic people, according to the CDC. With reduced access to abortion and other forms of reproductive healthcare, experts worry that these rates could rise in a post-Roe landscape. \AppleTypeServices Disparities in pregnancy-related deaths widened in 2020 In 2020, the risk of dying during or shortly after pregnancy for Black people increased by 25% and is 2.9 times the rate for White people. The pandemic year also saw a 38% increase in pregnancy-related deaths among Hispanic people. \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 These disparities are rooted in decades of structural disadvantages and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2021/08/25/us/visualizing-us-black-maternal-healthcare-inequities/index.html"}}{\fldrslt well-documented discrimination in medical care}}, leading to persisting gaps across socioeconomic and educational levels.\'93[Marginalized groups] really face barriers in every sense of the way,\'94 said Dr. Louis. \'93They face barriers in terms of getting care in a timely fashion, barriers in being able to see a health care provider, and then barriers to getting the appropriate treatment. And that\'92s even if they\'92re offered appropriate treatment.\'94 \AppleTypeServices Access to maternal care is harder to come by in states likely to ban abortion \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Access to maternal care is also worse in the 26 states that the Guttmacher Institute expects will be certain or likely to ban abortion. More than half of all counties in these states are classified as having low access to maternal care or are maternity-care deserts, according to a CNN analysis of data from the March of Dimes, compared to 39% of counties in states that are not likely to ban abortion if Roe is overturned. Nationwide, approximately 5.1 million women aged 15-44 live in areas with low access to maternal care \'97 or \'93maternity care deserts,\'94 according to a 2020 report from the{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.marchofdimes.org/research/maternity-care-deserts-report.aspx"}}{\fldrslt  March of Dimes}}, a nonprofit that advocates for better health care outcomes for mothers and babies. The organization defines a maternity care desert as any county where there is no hospital offering obstetric care, no birth center and no obstetric provider. In these counties, people carrying a pregnancy to term may face significant barriers in receiving quality care for both the parent and child. The 2020 average annual median household income for these counties was $49,518, below the national median household income of $67,521.\'94Those sorts of structural environments tend to go hand in hand,\'94 Rice said. \'93States with highly restrictive abortion environments also generally have fewer policies supporting health and well being of pregnant people, as well as their children and their families.\'94 \AppleTypeServices Legal abortions are low-risk and safe \'97 but lack of access to the procedure puts women at risk \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Negative health outcomes from receiving a legal abortion are rare \'97 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/70/ss/ss7009a1.htm"}}{\fldrslt according to the CDC}}, the national death rate from 2013-2018 was 0.41 deaths per 100,000 abortions. In 2018, the CDC identified only two patients who died as a result of a legal abortion. The rate of abortion-related fatalities has remained stable over the past several decades, even as maternal mortality rates have crept upwards. But people who seek to terminate their pregnancies and are unable to do so are more likely to face negative health outcomes, according to the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.ansirh.org/research/ongoing/turnaway-study"}}{\fldrslt Turnaway Study}}, a multi-year endeavor based at the University of California-San Francisco that tracked the health of people who were \'97 and were not \'97 able to receive a wanted abortion. The study found that women who were denied an abortion and gave birth reported more life-threatening conditions like eclampsia and postpartum hemorrhaging, in addition to higher levels of chronic conditions such as migraines and persistent joint pain, than women who were able to access the abortion. Two of the women in the study who were denied an abortion died from complications related to their pregnancy. Lauren Ralph, an epidemiologist who worked on the study at the University of California-San Francisco, described the deaths as \'93sobering.\'94 \'93I think we can say with certainty that those deaths could have been avoided had these people had access to the abortion care that they had sought,\'94 Ralph added. With Roe v. Wade overturned, Ralph and other experts have warned that the maternal mortality rate will likely continue to rise in the United States if pregnant people are unable to access the care they need. \'93It\'92s a wake up call that we should stop being so complacent and that we need to look at more proactive strategies,\'94 said Dr. Louis of the medical community\'92s role in providing safe access to abortion.\
\AppleTypeServices \
