Title: Louisiana woman claims she was denied an abortion after fetus was diagnosed with a fatal condition\
Author: Amanda Musa\
Publication_Date: Published 12:09 AM EDT, Sat August 20, 2022\
Article_Content:  CNN \'a0\'97\'a0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 A pregnant woman in Louisiana alleges that she was denied an abortion despite the fetus being diagnosed with a fatal condition. At about 10 weeks, Nancy Davis\'92 baby was diagnosed with acrania, a rare congenital disorder in which a fetus\'92 skull does not form inside of the womb, according to a statement from civil rights attorney Ben Crump, who represents Davis. Acrania is a lethal condition with death within the first week of life, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://fetalmedicine.org/education/fetal-abnormalities/brain/acrania"}}{\fldrslt according to the Fetal Medicine Foundation}}. However, after Davis decided to get an abortion, the hospital allegedly chose not to perform it, the statement said. \'93Ms. Nancy Davis was put in a horrifically cruel position by the State of Louisiana, left with only two choices: To carry the fetus until its inevitable death or to travel to another state to end the pregnancy weeks after she made the incredibly painful decision to do so,\'94 Crump said in a statement Thursday. Earlier this month, Davis {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.wafb.com/2022/08/15/mother-claims-she-was-denied-an-abortion-despite-babys-condition/"}}{\fldrslt spoke to CNN affiliate WAFB}} about her situation, saying doctors told her she would \'93be carrying the baby to bury the baby.\'94 In a statement to CNN on Friday, a spokesperson for Woman\'92s Hospital in Baton Rouge, Caroline Isemann, said the hospital cannot comment on a specific patient but said navigating an unviable pregnancy is extremely complex. \'93We look at each patient\'92s individual circumstances and how to remain in compliance with all current state laws to the best of our ability,\'94 Isemann told CNN. \'93Even if a specific diagnosis falls under medically futile exceptions provided by (the Louisiana Department of Health), the laws addressing treatment methods are much more complex and seemingly contradictory.\'94 Isemann {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2022/08/19/us/politics/louisiana-abortion-law.html"}}{\fldrslt told the New York Times }}that Louisiana\'92s multiple abortion bans, which use different terminology, complicate matters. \'93There is currently no guidance on which law controls\'94 the situation, she said, adding that the hospital was struggling to ensure that a doctor who terminates a pregnancy after a diagnosis of acrania was safe from prosecution.\AppleTypeServices  \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Meanwhile, the lawmaker who{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://legis.la.gov/legis/BillInfo.aspx?i=242567"}}{\fldrslt  wrote the state\'92s abortion law}}, state Sen. Katrina Jackson, told WAFB that Davis should have been allowed an abortion based on a list of 25 exclusive exceptions from the Louisiana Department of Health. \'93This woman is seeking a medical procedure for a pregnancy that is not viable outside of the womb,\'94 Jackson told WAFB. Crump\'92s office said the law is clearly having a negative impact. \'93Regardless of what Louisiana lawmakers claim, the law is having its intended effect, causing doctors to refuse to perform abortions even when they are medically necessary out of fear of losing their medical licenses or facing criminal charges,\'94 Crump said in a statement. As for Davis, Crump says she will be traveling out of state for the procedure, according to the statement.\AppleTypeServices \
