Title: States with restrictive abortion laws place more kids in foster care, particularly kids of color\
Author: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/profiles/jen-christensen"}}{\fldrslt Jen Christensen}}\
Publication_Date: Published 11:00 AM EST, Mon November 6, 2023\
Article_Content: CNN \'a0\'97\'a0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 A{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamapediatrics/fullarticle/10.1001/jamapediatrics.2023.4738?guestAccessKey=214250c5-4218-4eba-8bc7-2f938acae65d&utm_source=For_The_Media&utm_medium=referral&utm_campaign=ftm_links&utm_content=tfl&utm_term=110623"}}{\fldrslt  new study}} finds that in states with certain restrictive abortion laws, even before the US Supreme Court overturned Roe v. Wade, the number of children whose parents couldn\'92t or wouldn\'92t care for them increased and their children end up in foster care. The study, published Monday in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamapediatrics/fullarticle/10.1001/jamapediatrics.2023.4738?guestAccessKey=214250c5-4218-4eba-8bc7-2f938acae65d&utm_source=For_The_Media&utm_medium=referral&utm_campaign=ftm_links&utm_content=tfl&utm_term=110623"}}{\fldrslt JAMA Pediatrics}}, found that there was an 11% increase in children placed in foster care in states with certain abortion restrictions called TRAP laws, following the enactment of those TRAP laws, relative to states without such abortion restrictions. The study saw this increase by comparing the number of children who were conceived between 1990 and 2011 and placed in foster care between 2000 and 2020 in states with TRAP laws to those who lived in states without such laws. More than 4 million children went into foster care during this time period. Black children {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.aecf.org/blog/child-welfare-and-foster-care-statistics"}}{\fldrslt disproportionately got placed}} in foster care. TRAP stands for Targeted Restrictions on Abortion Providers. Ever since abortion became legal in 1973, states found ways to create laws that reduce access to abortion by restricting what clinics can and can\'92t do. Often restrictions become so burdensome, down to prescribing how long a hall in a clinic must be, clinics {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4999072/"}}{\fldrslt shut down}}. So, people seeking an abortion in these states may have a right to an abortion, but finding one is impossible. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.guttmacher.org/state-policy/explore/targeted-regulation-abortion-providers"}}{\fldrslt Twenty-three states}} have such restrictions. Anti-abortion politicians often argue TRAP laws protect mothers and children, but {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.aclu.org/news/reproductive-freedom/trap-laws-are-the-threat-to-abortion-rights-you-dont-know-about#:~:text=Typically%20cloaked%20in%20the%20language,major%20health%20organizations%20oppose%20them."}}{\fldrslt multiple studies}} and courts have found that the laws {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.guttmacher.org/gpr/2013/06/trap-laws-gain-political-traction-while-abortion-clinics-and-women-they-serve-pay-price"}}{\fldrslt do not make the procedure any safer}}. Compared to people who live in states without abortion access issues, studies have consistently shown that pregnant people who live in abortion-restrictive states typically face more problems, some of them are even deadly. People are {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33781761/"}}{\fldrslt much more likely}} to die in childbirth or die due to a pregnancy-related issues, particularly people of color who live in abortion restricted states, earlier studies have shown and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/12/14/health/maternal-infant-death-abortion-access/index.html"}}{\fldrslt so are their infants}}. People denied abortions are also much more likely to experience {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nber.org/system/files/working_papers/w26662/w26662.pdf"}}{\fldrslt financial distress.}} An 11% increase in the number of children put into foster care may not sound like a lot, but the foster care system is already overburdened. The situation became even more stressed during the pandemic. In 2022, more than half of all states saw a significant decline in the number of available foster care homes, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.fostercarecapacity.com/about"}}{\fldrslt one study showed.}} So, even an 11% increase could push the system into further jeopardy. With the Supreme Court decision to overturn Roe v. Wade, the situation isn\'92t likely to improve, according to study coauthor Dr. Savannah Atkins, a lecturer in Economics at Bentley University. \'93Now with a total restriction of abortion in certain states, we\'92re obviously going to see this being exacerbated,\'94 said Atkins. \'93We need to take into account these effects when we\'92re thinking of these, you know, sweeping legislations that regulate abortion.\'94 An editorial that accompanied the new study, written by doctors at Indiana University Medical School, highlighted the disproportionate burden abortion restrictions place on racial and ethnic minority families. The study found mainly families from these communities had to put children into foster care not due to neglect or abuse, but because they didn\'92t have adequate housing. \'93I thought it was really sad and devastating,\'94 said editorial co-author Dr. Tracey Wilkinson, an associate professor of pediatrics at Indiana University School of Medicine. \'93I think when people hear foster care, I think their head goes to a space of either neglect or abuse. And that\'92s not what\'92s happening here.\'94 Wilkinson said even when she sees patients who experience neglect or abuse, sometimes when she calls child protective services, the department cannot even return her calls; they are that overwhelmed with cases. \'93These long-term downstream impacts of abortion restrictions will significantly add to this burden,\'94 Wilkinson who is a pediatrician said. In the editorial, she and her colleague Dr. Caitlin Barnard, an assistant professor in the Department of Obstetrics and Gynecology at the Indiana University School of Medicine, pointed out what they say is flawed reasoning behind abortion restrictions. \'93This highlights the contradiction in the anti abortion position as it purports to protect women and families and at the same time, refuses to provide the support needed to safely raise their children,\'94 the editorial said. \'93It is a sad day when we are faced with statistical evidence that our national policy includes forcing women to carry pregnancies and deliver children only to take them away due to an inability to afford housing.\'94While there are loving foster families, children placed in foster care often fare worse when it comes to health, education, and income, than those who come from stable homes, particularly children of color, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://chlss.org/blog/study-shows-foster-care-is-bad-for-your-health/#:~:text=Using%20logistic%20regression%20models%2C%20researchers,as%20likely%20to%20feel%20anxiety"}}{\fldrslt research shows}}. Adkins says she knows firsthand that foster care can be good for children. Her own parents adopted some of her younger siblings out of foster care, but generally, being in foster care is not ideal for children. \'93If you think about research that has been done on the effects of people that are in the foster care system itself, they\'92re obviously affected negatively in terms of their education, their health, and their {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.childwelfare.gov/fostercaremonth/awareness/facts/"}}{\fldrslt mental health}},\'94 Adkins said. \'93So, it\'92s not just the burden that\'92s now placed on the foster care system that these abortion restrictions have had; it\'92s all these other effects, even after, that are now being impacted as well.\'94\AppleTypeServices \
