Title: Voters deliver ringing endorsement of abortion rights on midterm ballot initiatives across the US\
Author: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/profiles/veronica-stracqualursi"}}{\fldrslt Veronica Stracqualursi}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/profiles/devan-cole"}}{\fldrslt Devan Cole}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/profiles/paul-leblanc"}}{\fldrslt Paul LeBlanc}}\
Publication_Date: Updated 12:53 PM EST, Wed November 9, 2022\
Article_Content:  Washington CNN \'a0\'97\'a0\
\AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Voters in key states on Tuesday made their support for {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/09/13/politics/abortion-rights-what-matters/index.html"}}{\fldrslt abortion rights}} clear, affirming a months-long push by Democrats to act on a number of ballot measures in the wake of the Supreme Court\'92s decision {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.google.com/url?sa=t&rct=j&q=&esrc=s&source=web&cd=&cad=rja&uact=8&ved=2ahUKEwjtgvXyw6H7AhVKFVkFHbQSAOEQFnoECA8QAQ&url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cnn.com%2F2022%2F06%2F24%2Fpolitics%2Fdobbs-mississippi-supreme-court-abortion-roe-wade&usg=AOvVaw0QOcpz84Yjmdmsn7AOqfBE"}}{\fldrslt overturning Roe v. Wade}}. Several states moved to enshrine abortion protections in their constitutions and others rejected proposals to limit abortion access or criminalize doctors in some cases. Democratic lawmakers and organizers cast the midterm elections as a referendum on Republican efforts to limit women\'92s choices, and the notable electoral reaction could serve as a warning sign for future GOP efforts to restrict the procedure at the state-level. \AppleTypeServices Voters affirmed abortion rights in all five states with amendments, CNN projects Voters approved ballot measures in California, Michigan and Vermont to protect abortion rights, according to CNN projections. Amendments that would have further restricted abortion rights in Kentucky and Montana were both rejected.\AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 About 27% of voters cited abortion as the issue most important to them, according to the preliminary results of the national and state exit polls conducted for CNN and other news networks by Edison Research. The results also showed that when it comes to the issue, roughly half of voters said they trusted Democratic candidates, compared with more than 4 in 10 voters who said they trusted Republican candidates. \'93This fall, Roe is on the ballot,\'94 President Joe Biden declared in a defiant speech from the White House just hours after the Supreme Court\'92s ruling earlier this year. While CNN projected some anti-abortion Republicans {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/11/08/politics/2022-midterm-election-day-takeaways/index.html"}}{\fldrslt will win their races}}, voters in five states moved to affirm abortion rights. Here\'92s a running list of what voters decided on {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/"}}{\fldrslt Election Day}}. \AppleTypeServices Montana rejects abortion measure that would allow criminal penalties on health care providers \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Voters in Montana rejected on Tuesday proposed legislation that would have imposed criminal penalties on health care providers who do not act to preserve the life of infants born during the course of an abortion, CNN projects. LR-131, if adopted, would have provided that an infant \'93born alive\'94 \'96 defined as an infant \'93at any stage of development\'94 who breathes, has a beating heart or definite movement of voluntary muscles after expulsion or extraction \'96 be treated as a legal person entitled to medical treatment. \AppleTypeServices Montana decides against further restricting abortion, CNN projects Montana voters rejected a ballot measure that would require medical care for infants born alive, including after an abortion, according to a CNN projection. As of Wednesday evening, more than 448,000 had voted on the amendment, with the majority against. \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 A health care provider who violated the proposed law would have been guilty of a felony and could have faced up to 20 years in state prison and/or a fine of up to $50,000. It would have also mandated that health care providers and clinics report \'93a failure to comply with the requirements\'94 to law enforcement. Montana currently prohibits abortions past viability \'96 \'93the ability of a fetus to live outside the mother\'92s womb\'94 \'96 except to save the life or health of the woman. Last year, the state\'92s Republican-led legislature passed the bill that put the referendum on the ballot. Backers of the measure said such a law was necessary to protect infants born during an abortion attempt, while opponents said the bill wasn\'92t needed because there are laws in place that require care to be given. Hillary-Anne Crosby, the campaign coordinator and communications lead for Compassion for Montana Families, previously said LR-131 \'93zeroes in on families that are having complications in the labor and delivery room, such as lethal fetal abnormalities.\'94 \'93It\'92s not uncommon for families to make the decision to induce labor so that they can hold their infant for a few minutes, maybe have family come in and be able to meet their new family member for the few moments that they are alive, and LR-131 throws a wrench in that being a viable option to them without the health care workers facing a felony,\'94 she previously told CNN. \AppleTypeServices Kentucky rejects proposal that would have further restricted abortion rights \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Kentucky voters on Tuesday rejected a proposal to amend the state\'92s constitution to say that it does not \'93secure or protect a right\'94 to abortion or the funding of abortion, CNN projects. The ballot question voters faced read: \'93Are you in favor of amending the Constitution of Kentucky by creating a new Section of the Constitution to be numbered Section 26A to state as follows: To protect human life, nothing in this Constitution shall be construed to secure or protect a right to abortion or require the funding of abortion?\'94 Kentucky\'92s \'93trigger law,\'94 which bans most abortions at all stages of pregnancy, and a law banning abortion after roughly six weeks of pregnancy {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/08/01/politics/kentucky-abortion-ban/index.html"}}{\fldrslt have been allowed to be enforced temporarily}} while a lawsuit challenging the laws continues. Kentucky Right to Life executive director Addia Wuchner, who chairs the Yes for Life Alliance, which supported Amendment 2, previously said voting \'93yes\'94 would \'93ensure there\'92s no false interpretation of the constitution.\'94 \AppleTypeServices Kentucky decides not to further restrict abortion rights, CNN projects Kentucky voted against amending the state constitution to say it does not "secure or protect a right" to an abortion or funding of abortion, according to a CNN projection. As of Tuesday morning, more than 1.4 million had voted on the amendment, with the majority against. \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Without the amendment, \'93instead of the lawmakers who duly reflect the people\'92s will, we would end up with the abortion industry taking each law back into court,\'94 Wuchner said. Tamarra Wieder, the Kentucky state director for Planned Parenthood Alliance Advocates, had said passing the amendment would \'93open the door to more attacks on abortion access,\'94 but rejecting it would allow abortion rights advocates to \'93continue to fight back\'94 against the six-week ban and the trigger ban. If adopted, the measure would have gone into effect immediately once the results of the election are certified by the State Board of Elections. \AppleTypeServices Michigan enshrines abortion rights \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Michigan voters on Tuesday voted to enshrine abortion rights in the state\'92s constitution, a move that will help block a decades-old abortion ban from taking effect, CNN projects. The passage of ballot Proposal 3 amends the Michigan constitution to establish an \'93individual right to reproductive freedom, including right to make and carry out all decisions about pregnancy.\'94 Michigan has a 1931 law that essentially bans abortion in the state, but that law is being blocked by the courts. The passage of the ballot proposal helps prevent the ban from taking effect. The amendment allows the state to regulate abortion after fetal viability, except if needed to protect a patient\'92s life or physical or mental health. It also bars the state from prosecuting an individual for having an abortion or miscarriage or from prosecuting someone who assists a pregnant person in \'93exercising rights established by this amendment.\'94 \AppleTypeServices Michigan surpasses 2018 turnout to guarantee right to an abortion Michigan voted to protect abortion access in the state constitution, according to a CNN projection, preventing a 1931 law banning abortion from taking effect. More Michiganders have voted on the amendment than the total number of people who participated in the 2018 midterm election. \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 The proposal had to overcome legal challenges to be included on the ballot, with the Michigan Supreme Court {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/09/08/politics/michigan-supreme-court-abortion-ballot-initiative"}}{\fldrslt ordering officials in September}} to include the question on ballots in a 5-2 ruling. \'93We are energized and motivated now more than ever to restore the protections that were lost under Roe,\'94 Darci McConnell, a spokesperson for Reproductive Freedom for All, a group backing the effort, said in a statement after the ruling. Michigan Republicans had blasted the court\'92s decision, along with another on a voting rights ballot proposal. \'93Despite the court ruling, these measures remain too extreme for Michigan, and we are certain they will be handily defeated at the ballot box in November,\'94 Elizabeth Giannone, deputy communications director for the state party, predicted in a statement earlier this year. \AppleTypeServices California voters put abortion rights in state constitution \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 The California Constitution will protect the right to an abortion after residents on Tuesday passed a ballot initiative to enshrine the right in the state\'92s governing document, CNN projects. \AppleTypeServices California votes to protect abortion rights, CNN projects California voted to include reproductive rights in the state constitution, according to a CNN projection. As of Thursday evening, more than 9.4 million Californians had voted on the amendment, with the majority in support. \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Currently, the state constitution guarantees a right to privacy, which the California Supreme Court has ruled includes the right to have an abortion. In May, following the leak of the US Supreme Court\'92s draft opinion to overturn Roe v. Wade, California Democratic leaders Gov. Gavin Newsom, state Senate President Pro Tempore Toni Atkins and state Assembly Speaker Anthony Rendon said in a statement that they would propose an amendment \'93so that there is no doubt as to the right to abortion in this state.\'94 The Democratic-controlled state legislature in June approved putting the amendment on the November ballot. \'93Proposition 1 ensures that no matter what the future legislature looks like, what the future governor looks like, that people in California have a constitutional protection that explicitly ensures the state won\'92t interfere with their right to reproductive freedom,\'94 Jodi Hicks, the head of Planned Parenthood Affiliates of California and co-chair of the Yes on Prop 1 campaign, previously told CNN. The California Family Council had said the proposed amendment is an \'93extreme and costly proposal that does nothing to advance women\'92s health.\'94 And the California Catholic Conference, which opposes Proposition 1, called it a \'93misleading ballot measure that allows unlimited late-term abortions \'96 for any reason, at any time, even moments before birth, paid for by tax dollars.\'94 The Yes on Prop 1 campaign previously said the proposal would not change \'93existing state constitutional protections and law, which provide for the right to choose an abortion prior to viability or to protect the pregnant person\'92s life or health.\'94 The measure goes into effect the fifth day after the vote is certified. \AppleTypeServices Vermont voters back abortion rights \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Voters in Vermont on Tuesday approved an amendment to the state\'92s constitution that abortion rights supporters say will protect \'93every person\'92s right to make their own reproductive decisions,\'94 including about pregnancies, abortion and birth control, CNN projects. The Vermont Constitution will now be amended to read: \'93That an individual\'92s right to personal reproductive autonomy is central to the liberty and dignity to determine one\'92s own life course and shall not be denied or infringed unless justified by a compelling State interest achieved by the least restrictive means.\'94 Abortion is currently legal at all stages of pregnancy in Vermont. The proposed amendment was {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/09/us/vermont-reproductive-liberty-constitution-amendment-trnd"}}{\fldrslt first brought by the Vermont Legislature in 2019}}. Vermont for Reproductive Liberty Ballot Committee, the coalition that backed Article 22, had previously said state-level protections \'93are vital to safeguarding access\'94 now that the US Supreme Court has overturned Roe v. Wade. \'93It would mean that abortion access has been codified in the state constitution, and really the most important part of that is that it\'92s protected long-term, and it means that access is going to be there, no matter what our politicians do,\'94 Sam Donnelly, the campaign manager for the coalition, previously told CNN. \AppleTypeServices Vermont surpasses 2018 turnout to vote to guarantee right to abortion More voters in Vermont cast their ballots to safeguard abortion access in the state constitution than the total number of people who participated in the 2018 midterm election. \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Both supporters and opponents of Article 22 have said its adoption means that Vermont lawmakers will be unable to pass any limitations or regulations on abortion in the future because it would then be deemed unconstitutional. Mary Beerworth, the executive director of the Vermont Right to Life Committee, which opposes the amendment, had said the proposal goes \'93way, way further\'94 than codifying abortion rights into the state constitution. \'93It will be about a vast range of anything that pertains to your personal reproductive autonomy, from surrogacy, three-parent embryo, designer babies, minors possibly accessing the hormone blockers for transgender surgery without their parents\'92 knowledge or consent,\'94 she previously told CNN. \'93It\'92s opening a whole new world here if it passes.\'94\
