Title: How the Supreme Court recalibrated the abortion debate in just 3 words\
Author: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/profiles/eliott-c-mclaughlin-profile"}}{\fldrslt Eliott C. McLaughlin}}\
Publication_Date:Updated 11:02 AM EDT, Sun July 17, 2022\
Article_Content: CNN \'a0\'97\'a0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 It\'92s not just that US Supreme Court majorities upheld Mississippi\'92s 15-week abortion ban and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/06/24/politics/dobbs-mississippi-supreme-court-abortion-roe-wade/index.html"}}{\fldrslt overturned Roe v. Wade}}. The opinion also skewed the crux of the conversation going forward \'96 with just three words. \'93Unborn human being\'94 is the term Associate Justice Samuel Alito adopted from the Mississippi statute, thereby replacing {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.law.cornell.edu/supremecourt/text/410/113"}}{\fldrslt the key phrase in the landmark 1973 Roe ruling}} that spelled out a constitutional right to abortion: \'93potential life.\'94 It may seem like a semantic argument. Experts say it\'92s anything but. Alito didn\'92t write God or Christianity or Bible anywhere {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/06/24/politics/dobbs-v-jackson-womens-health-organization-opinion-text/index.html"}}{\fldrslt in the opinion}}, but his justification is a veiled \'93religious narrative,\'94 said {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.elon.edu/u/directory/profile/?user=rpeters"}}{\fldrslt Rebecca Todd Peters}}, a religious studies professor at Elon University. By co-opting the language in Mississippi\'92s law in Dobbs v. Jackson Women\'92s Health Organization, the majority opinion gives credence to the notion \'96 embraced largely by the religious right \'96 that life begins at fertilization, she said. The ruling has already emboldened several states {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/interactive/2022/us/abortion-laws-access-by-state/index.html"}}{\fldrslt to ban and criminalize the medical procedure}} in almost all circumstances. \'93That is an enormous shift,\'94 Peters said. \'93It erases whole groups of people who have different religious beliefs.\'94 Peters, who is ordained in the Presbyterian Church, isn\'92t merely speaking about Christians. When a zygote, embryo or fetus becomes a human being is far from an objective determination within or across any religions. There is no scientific gauge: Doctors tend to focus on viability, which experts {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.acog.org/womens-health/faqs/extremely-preterm-birth"}}{\fldrslt believe to be around 23 weeks}}, though health outcomes {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://healthcare.utah.edu/womenshealth/pregnancy-birth/preterm-birth/when-is-it-safe-to-deliver.php"}}{\fldrslt improve the longer the gestational period}}. Various religions have relied on a range of wayposts, including fertilization, quickening (when the mother feels the fetus moving), when the embryo develops a heartbeat, ensoulment and birth. Confounding matters is that, just like in Christian sects, there are chasms of disagreement among other religions \'96 not only regarding personhood but also a woman\'92s bodily autonomy \'96 making holy texts a troublesome barometer for whether abortion should be outlawed. Worse, said Peters, is that by co-opting the term, \'93unborn human being,\'94 it signals \'93which religious voices get authority and power in our country.\'94 Though opponents of legalized abortion often paint women who undergo abortions as heathens, a strong majority \'96 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.guttmacher.org/report/characteristics-us-abortion-patients-2014"}}{\fldrslt more than 6 in 10}} \'96 identified as women of faith in a 2014 poll, said Peters, who is on sabbatical for a research project titled, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.elon.edu/u/news/2021/10/05/toddie-peters-awarded-emory-university-rise-grant/"}}{\fldrslt \'93Abortion and Religion: Listening to Women.\'94}} \'93There are a whole lot more who support bodily autonomy for mothers to make decisions about life and how many children they have and who they have them with and how to shape their future with or without partners,\'94 Peters said. \'93We\'92ve allowed a minority religious belief to curtail the rights of the majority of women in the country. I feel like I\'92m in the middle of a dystopian novel.\'94 More than 50 religious groups sought to make this clear to the high court last year, filing a friend-of-the-court brief explaining religious traditions have various views of when life begins, affirm a woman\'92s \'93moral right\'94 to decide when to terminate pregnancy and stand by \'93the importance of ensuring reproductive choice for women in marginalized communities who are disproportionately harmed by the ban.\'94 \'93By prohibiting abortions beyond 15 weeks gestation, the Ban precludes women from making that choice in accordance with their own moral, spiritual, and religious beliefs, which this Court has recognized as a constitutional right,\'94 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.supremecourt.gov/DocketPDF/19/19-1392/192931/20210920125529079_19-1392%20Dobbs%20v%20Jackson%20Womens%20Health%20Brief%20of%20Amici%20Curiae%20Catholics%20for%20Church%20et%20al.pdf"}}{\fldrslt the brief said}}. The attitude that a woman would have to justify her decision to others is \'93rooted in religion,\'94 Peters said. It robs women of their autonomy and espouses a narrow, archaic view of Christianity that has long been malappropriated to dictate \'93women are to be subservient and meant to be child bearers,\'94 she said. \AppleTypeServices Religions and religious people vary widely \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 A {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://news.gallup.com/poll/1576/abortion.aspx"}}{\fldrslt Gallup poll in May}} \'96 before Roe\'92s reversal \'96 found 55% of Americans identified as \'93pro-choice,\'94 while 39% said they\'92re \'93pro-life.\'94 Only 13% of Americans said abortions should be prohibited across the board, and 53% said abortions should be legal in most or all circumstances, Gallup reported. Breaking the percentages down by dogma demonstrates only a handful of groups \'96 Jehovah\'92s Witnesses (68%), Mormons (66%) White evangelical Protestants (65%), Hispanic Protestants (58%) and Hispanic Catholics (52%) \'96 count a majority of members as opposing abortion,{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.prri.org/research/legal-in-most-cases-the-impact-of-the-abortion-debate-in-2019-america/"}}{\fldrslt  the nonprofit Public Religion Research Institute}} found in 2018. Catholics have long driven the debate on abortion \'96 and five Catholics and a justice who was raised Catholic upheld Mississippi\'92s 15-week ban \'96 even as the institute\'92s data suggests 52% of White Catholics are OK with legal abortion. (It is worth noting Associate Justice Sonia Sotomayor broke with her fellow Catholics in Dobbs.) Here is a look at support for legal abortion in most or all cases among other religions, per the institute: Muslims \'96 51% Orthodox Christian \'96 54% Black Protestants \'96 56% White mainline Protestants \'96 59% Hindus \'96 62% Buddhists \'96 69% Jewish people \'96 70% And {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.pewresearch.org/religion/2022/05/06/americans-views-on-whether-and-in-what-circumstances-abortion-should-be-legal/"}}{\fldrslt 87% of agnostics and 97% of atheists }}expressed support for abortion in all or most cases, the Pew Research Center reported this year. Those numbers are black and white, of course, but religions and their adherents are not, so to cast attitudes as \'93for\'94 or \'93against\'94 disappears nuance from the equation. There are other factors to consider, experts say. Islamic scholars, for instance, took a more liberal stance in premodern times, said {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://law.ucla.edu/faculty/faculty-profiles/khaled-m-abou-el-fadl"}}{\fldrslt UCLA law professor Khaled Abou El Fadl}}, an Islamic jurist who holds a doctorate in Islamic law from Princeton University. There was a time when women so often miscarried in the first trimester that some jurists didn\'92t regard the fetus as a full human being, while others debated when the soul enters the fetus \'96 somewhere between 40 and 120 days, the professor said. Still, there were some conservative-minded jurists who felt the \'93potentiality of life\'94 should always be protected, he said. The conversation began to shift during colonialism, with the influence of French law and the creation of state governments, Abou El Fadl said. \'93It\'92s interesting because the medieval debate in Islamic law was about when the soul enters the body. We don\'92t have an Islamic text on that \'96 nothing in the Quran, nothing in the inherited traditions of the Prophet Muhammad that answers the question,\'94 he said, explaining that once \'93the state became much larger in everyone\'92s life and the whole idea (arises) that the state has the right to regulate and enforce morality,\'94 most if not all Muslim nations banned abortion except to save the mother\'92s life. Judaism takes a similar position on allowing abortion to save the mother. \'93Judaism is a religion that is based on law,\'94 and there are no religious figures \'96 no popes or imams \'96 who can allow something Jewish law prohibits, said Dr. Daniel Eisenberg, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.jewishmedicalethics.com/about.html"}}{\fldrslt an expert in Jewish medical ethics}} and a radiologist at Einstein Medical Center Philadelphia. The issue of when life begins is not a Jewish concept, he said. The question is: When does Jewish law protect life? The general consensus is when it\'92s necessary to protect a mother\'92s life. Outside that, \'93the range of opinions is from a Biblically forbidden form of murder without being a capital offense to being a rabbinic prohibition that is very serious but not murder.\'94 Abortion is {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://aish.com/48954946/"}}{\fldrslt never a capital offense in Jewish law}}, he said. \'93A fetus is going to become a full-fledged human being, but it is not considered to be a full-fledged human being until it is born. But not being a human being does not mean it\'92s nothing,\'94 said Eisenberg, who has spent years studying and lecturing on the Talmud and Jewish law. \'93The concept is that the fetus is a person with slightly less protection than a full-fledged human being, than the mother. \'85 When it is a threat to the mother, it is subordinate.\'94 There is no official position in Buddhism, and Buddhist scholars vary, with some saying the fetus is a human at fertilization and various others saying personhood begins weeks or even five months later, author and lay dharma teacher Sallie Jiko Tisdale {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tricycle.org/trikedaily/buddhism-abortion/"}}{\fldrslt wrote last year in the quarterly, Tricycle: The Buddhist Review}}. \'93Nevertheless, the conclusion of orthodox Buddhist scholars has long been that a human being appears at the moment of conception. Because human birth is a rare and precious gift, to deprive a being of the opportunity is a grave mistake,\'94 she wrote. Hindu teachings elevate the life of the mother and support a ban on abortion except to save her life, experts say. \'93Abortion deliberately disrupts the process of reincarnation and kills an innocent human being \'85 and imposes serious karmic burdens on its agent,\'94 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7166242/"}}{\fldrslt wrote Dr. Kiarash Aramesh}}, director of the James F. Drane Bioethics Institute at Edinboro University, in 2019. \'93The perspective of Hinduism is a very pro-life one, emphasizing Ahimsa (not causing harm to living creatures) and its intrinsic reverence for life.\'94 Across all religions, scholars can further diverge when the issues of birth defects, rape, incest and the mother\'92s mental health are at play. Older texts provide little guidance on the latter because sensitivity to mental health is a relatively new concentration in medicine, experts say. Many Jewish scholars see the law as condoning abortion if the mother exhibits suicidal ideation, Eisenberg said. Some Islamic scholars feel suicide is a choice, Abou El Fadl said, but as a jurist, he understands many who contemplate suicide feel they have no choice and he\'92d consider each case on its own merits. As for rape and incest, Islamic scholars are split, he said, but he points out even in Egypt, where abortion is forbidden in cases of rape and incest, it\'92s rarely if ever prosecuted. In Judaism, the law\'92s interpretations are so varied on rape and incest, Eisenberg suggested it warranted a news article to itself. Abortion following the detection of birth defects, lethal or otherwise, also divides rabbis, he said, but he points out that despite the American debate\'92s focus on rape, incest and birth defects, those reasons prompt only a small fraction of abortion procedures. Most commonly, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.guttmacher.org/sites/default/files/pdfs/tables/370305/3711005t2.pdf"}}{\fldrslt women seek abortion because}} a child would disrupt their lives or because they cannot afford a baby \'96 reasons, Eisenberg said,{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.ou.org/news/statement-by-the-union-of-orthodox-jewish-congregations-of-america-on-us-supreme-courts-potential-overturning-of-roe-v-wade/"}}{\fldrslt  traditional Jewish law would never condone}}. As the polling suggests, certain groups and branches of the faith hold different views. Elsewhere on the spectrum is the politically progressive Reform Judaism \'96 the country\'92s largest denomination, accounting for {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2021/06/22/denominational-switching-among-u-s-jews-reform-judaism-has-gained-conservative-judaism-has-lost/"}}{\fldrslt a third of American Jews}} \'96 which holds a mother {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://reformjudaism.org/learning/answers-jewish-questions/what-reform-jewish-perspective-abortion"}}{\fldrslt maintains total autonomy}} when deciding {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.ncjw.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/NCJW_ReproductiveGuide_Final.pdf"}}{\fldrslt whether to terminate}} a pregnancy. \AppleTypeServices \'91They also believe God forgives sins\'92 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 For Peters, the debate should revolve around a woman\'92s right to control her fate, she said. As {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.elon.edu/u/news/2022/01/24/in-my-words-religious-women-have-abortions-too-and-many-faiths-affirm-abortion-rights/"}}{\fldrslt she cowrote in a January column}}, \'93It often seems religion is not even a relevant statistical data point in understanding who gets abortions. In fact, 62 percent of women who have abortions identify as women of faith. Religiously identified women, with the notable exception of evangelical women, have abortions at virtually the same rate as their representation in the population.\'94 Yet proponents of outlawing abortion continue to perpetuate a false binary, \'93this sort of popular perception that religion is against abortion and all the people for abortion are secular \'96 and that is just not true at all,\'94 she said. \'93It\'92s a dangerous narrative that has shaped our culture\'92s understanding of abortion.\'94 Peters has interviewed dozens of women for \'93Abortion and Religion: Listening to Women,\'94 including those who opposed abortion rights before terminating their own pregnancies. She\'92s found women often have abortions out of a love they feel coincides with their religions, she said. The debate is so \'93stigmatized and mean-spirited\'94 and women are stereotyped and caricatured, but Peters has found women have \'93very complex, complicated, unique experiences\'94 and pursue abortions because they can\'92t give a child what she or he deserves materially and spiritually. They experience a host of feelings, sometimes contradictory: sadness and happiness, relief and guilt. \'93Nobody\'92s confused. There\'92s no sense of, \'91Did I do the right thing?\'92\'94 she said. \'93There are women who feel guilty, who feel like having an abortion may be a sin, but they also believe God forgives sins.\'94 Abou El Fadl doesn\'92t consider himself pro-abortion. He wouldn\'92t want his daughter to terminate a pregnancy, but as a jurist, he cannot be bound to a single issue, he said. He {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.searchforbeauty.org/2015/01/04/fatwa-on-the-permissibility-of-abortion/"}}{\fldrslt must consider the totality of circumstances}}, and he worries about a Supreme Court hewing to an originalist perspective endorsed by Founding Fathers who accepted slavery and all sorts of discrimination. This is largely the same high court that upheld President Donald Trump\'92s \'93Muslim ban,\'94 he noted. \'93Muslims, who are already targets of Islamophobia and incredible amounts of racism, do we really want to live in a country with less rights?\'94 he asked. \'93It\'92s very hard for me to forget about the role of the state and say it\'92s a simple matter of: Do we kill babies or do we not kill babies?\'94\AppleTypeServices  \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Whether she\'92s escorting women to a clinic, teaching at Elon or simply having dinner with friends and family, Peters said, she\'92s guided by Scripture \'96 verses that command she care for the poor and marginalized, love her neighbors and seek social justice. To those who\'92d call her abortion views heretical, she\'92d point out the Bible says nothing explicitly about abortion. She\'92s also never found a pregnant woman who was not invested in what might happen to her potential child. Suggesting otherwise \'96 or pitting a mother against her fetus for political points \'96 is more than problematic, she said. \'93Pitting women against their prenate is a fiction we are now building our legal system around, and I think that\'92s very dangerous,\'94 she said. \'93The problem is the belief that life begins at conception is a theological belief. \'85 I think it\'92s a bit of a false argument in the sense that it\'92s not a theological belief that people are fully autonomous individuals with legal and human rights. The idea a fertilized egg should be afforded the exact same rights \'96 it\'92s fine to have that belief if you don\'92t impose it on others.\'94\AppleTypeServices \
