Title: Louisiana woman who alleges she was denied abortion after fetus\'92 fatal diagnosis says \'91it should not happen to any other woman\'92\
Author: Ray Sanchez and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/profiles/melissa-alonso"}}{\fldrslt Melissa Alonso}}\
Publication_Date:  Published 1:48 PM EDT, Fri August 26, 2022\
Article_Content: CNN \'a0\'97\'a0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 A pregnant Louisiana woman who {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/08/20/us/louisiana-abortion-fatal-condition/index.html"}}{\fldrslt alleges she was denied an abortion}} despite the fetus being diagnosed with a fatal condition says other women should not have to experience her plight. Nancy Davis said she is planning to get an abortion in another state after a Louisiana hospital allegedly chose not to perform the procedure even though her baby was diagnosed with acrania, a rare congenital disorder in which a fetus\'92 skull does not form inside of the womb. Acrania is a lethal condition with death within the first week of life, according to the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://fetalmedicine.org/education/fetal-abnormalities/brain/acrania"}}{\fldrslt Fetal Medicine Foundation.}} Davis\'92 case reflects the confusion and wrenching decisions faced by mothers and health care professionals after the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/politics/live-news/roe-wade-abortion-supreme-court-ruling/index.html"}}{\fldrslt June 24 US Supreme Court ruling}} to overturn the constitutional right to an abortion. Laws that ban abortion or severely restrict the procedure {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/08/25/politics/where-abortion-banned-states-court-legal-challenges/index.html"}}{\fldrslt have subsequently gone into effect in about a dozen states}} \'96 Louisiana among them. \'93I want you to imagine what it\'92s been like to continue this pregnancy for another six weeks after this diagnosis,\'94 Davis said at a news conference on the steps of the Louisiana State Capitol in Baton Rouge. \'93This is not fair to me and it should not happen to any other woman.\'94 Davis, who said she learned of the baby\'92s fatal condition 10 weeks into her pregnancy, was joined at the news conference by the baby\'92s father and her attorneys, including Ben Crump. \'93The doctors told me that my baby would die shortly after birth,\'94 Davis said. \'93They told me that I should terminate the pregnancy. Because of the state of Louisiana\'92s abortion ban they cannot perform the procedure. Basically, they said I had to carry my baby to bury my baby. They seemed confused about the law and afraid of what would happen to them if they perform a criminal abortion, according to the law.\'94 In a statement last week, a spokesperson for Woman\'92s Hospital in Baton Rouge, Caroline Isemann, said the hospital cannot comment on a specific patient but said navigating an unviable pregnancy is extremely complex. \'93We look at each patient\'92s individual circumstances and how to remain in compliance with all current state laws to the best of our ability,\'94 Isemann told CNN. \'93Even if a specific diagnosis falls under medically futile exceptions provided by (the Louisiana Department of Health), the laws addressing treatment methods are much more complex and seemingly contradictory.\'94 Crump called on the state to hold a special session of the Louisiana legislature to address the \'93public health catastrophe\'94 created by \'93vague and confusing\'94 abortion laws. The attorney said Louisiana lawmakers have \'93inflicted unspeakable pain, emotional damage and physical risk\'94 by stepping between his client and her doctors. He said other women and healthcare providers will endure a similar plight because state law has \'93created an environment of confusion and fear.\'94 Isemann told The {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2022/08/19/us/politics/louisiana-abortion-law.html"}}{\fldrslt New York Times }}that Louisiana\'92s multiple abortion bans, which use different terminology, complicate matters. \'93There is currently no guidance on which law controls\'94 the situation, she said, adding that the hospital was struggling to ensure that a doctor who terminates a pregnancy after a diagnosis of acrania was safe from prosecution. The lawmaker who wrote the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://legis.la.gov/legis/BillInfo.aspx?i=242567"}}{\fldrslt state\'92s abortion law}}, state Sen. Katrina Jackson, told {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.wafb.com/2022/08/16/la-lawmaker-brings-clarity-abortion-confusion/"}}{\fldrslt CNN affiliate WAFB }}that Davis should have been allowed an abortion based on a list of 25 exclusive exceptions from the Louisiana Department of Health. \'93This woman is seeking a medical procedure for a pregnancy that is not viable outside of the womb,\'94 Jackson told WAFB. It\'92s unclear which state Davis will go to for the abortion. \'93Davis and her family are very grateful to all of those who donated to her to be able to arrange for travel,\'94 Crump said. \'93By the time Ms. Davis has the procedure she needs next week, she would have carried this unsustainable pregnancy for an additional month and a half,\'94 with \'93risks and emotional tolls.\'94 The father of the baby, Chedrick Cole, said, \'93From afar it\'92s very easy to have an opinion about something but until you\'92re actually in this situation and going through it, you don\'92t understand how complex it is. I also want to say that we must continue to raise consciousness and awareness about situations like this because it\'92s happening all over. \'85 And it\'92s so much bigger than us and our family.\'94\AppleTypeServices \
