Title: These women ran an underground abortion network in the 1960s. Here\'92s what they fear might happen today\
Author: \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Sandee LaMotte\AppleTypeServices \
Publication_Date: \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Updated 11:08 AM EDT, Sun April 23, 2023\AppleTypeServices \
Article_Content: CNN \'a0\'97\'a0\AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 The voice on the phone in 1966 was gruff and abrupt: \'93Do you want the Chevy, the Cadillac or the Rolls Royce?\'94 A Chevy abortion would cost about $200, cash in hand, the voice explained. A Cadillac was around $500, and the Rolls Royce was $1,000. \'93You can\'92t afford more than the Chevy? Fine,\'94 the voice growled. \'93Go to this address at this time. Don\'92t be late and don\'92t forget the cash.\'94 The voice disappeared. Dorie Barron told CNN she recalls staring blankly at the phone in her hand, startled by the sudden empty tone. Then it hit her: She had just arranged an illegal abortion with the Chicago Mafia. \AppleTypeServices \'91All of a sudden they were gone\'92 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 The motel Barron was sent to was in an unfamiliar part of Chicago, a scary \'93middle of nowhere,\'94 she said. She was told to go to a specific room, sit on the bed and wait. Suddenly three men and a woman came in the door. \'93I was petrified. They spoke all of three sentences to me the entire time: \'91Where\'92s the money?\'92 \'91Lie back and do as I tell you.\'92 And finally \'91Get in the bathroom,\'92\'94 when the abortion was over, Barron said. \'93Then all of a sudden they were gone.\'94 Bleeding profusely, Barron managed to find a cab to take her home. When the bleeding didn\'92t stop, her bed-ridden mother made her go to the hospital. At 24, Barron was taking care of her ailing mother and her 2-year-old daughter when she discovered she was pregnant. Her boyfriend, who had no job and lived with his parents, \'93freaked,\'94 said Barron, who appears in a recent HBO documentary. The boyfriend suggested she get an abortion. She had never considered that option. \'93But what was I to do? My mom was taking care of my daughter from her bed while I worked \'97 they would read and play games until I got home,\'94 Barron said.\'94How was either of us going to cope with a baby? \'93Looking back, I realize I was taking my life in my hands,\'94 said Barron, now an 81-year-old grandmother. \'93To this day it gives me chills. If I had died, what in God\'92s green earth would have happened to my mom and daughter?\'94 \AppleTypeServices Few rights for women \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Women in the 1960s endured restrictions relatively unknown to women today. The so-called \'93fairer sex\'94 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2014/08/07/living/sixties-women-5-things/index.html"}}{\fldrslt could not serve on juries}} and often could not get an Ivy League education. Women earned about half as much as a man doing the same job and were seldom promoted. Women could not get a credit card unless they were married \'97 and then only if their husband co-signed. The same applied to birth control \'97 only the married need apply. More experienced women shared a workaround with the uninitiated: \'93Go to Woolworth, buy a cheap wedding-type ring and wear it to your doctor\'92s appointment. And don\'92t forget to smile.\'94 Marital rape wasn\'92t{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://vawnet.org/material/marital-rape-new-research-and-directions#:~:text=On%20July%205%2C%201993%2C%20marital,rape%20prosecution%20granted%20to%20husbands."}}{\fldrslt  legally }}considered rape. And, of course, women had no legal right to terminate a pregnancy until four states \'97 Alaska, Hawaii, New York and Washington \'97 legalized abortion in 1970, three years before Roe v. Wade became the law of the land. Illinois had no such protection, said Heather Booth, a lifelong feminist activist and political strategist: \'93Three people discussing having an abortion in Chicago in 1965 was a conspiracy to commit felony murder.\'94Despite that danger, a courageous band of young women \'97 most in their 20\'92s, some in college, some married with children \'97 banded together in Chicago to create an underground abortion network. The group was officially created in 1969 as the \'93Abortion Counseling Service of Women\'92s Liberation.\'94 But after running ads in an underground newspaper: \'93Pregnant? Don\'92t want to be? Call Jane,\'94 each member of the group answered the phone as \'93Jane.\'94 \'93We were co-conspirators with the women who called us,\'94 said 75-year-old Laura Kaplan, who published a book about the service in 1997 entitled \'93{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.amazon.com/The-Story-of-Jane-Laura-Kaplan-audiobook/dp/B07PH2MHF3/ref=sr_1_1?crid=ZUHPW86V6NJL&keywords=laura+kaplan+the+story+of+jane&qid=1669904993&s=books&sprefix=laura+kaplan+the+story+of+jane%2Cstripbooks%2C79&sr=1-1"}}{\fldrslt The Story of Jane: The Legendary Underground Feminist Abortion Service.\'94}} \'93We\'92ll protect you; we hope you\'92ll protect us,\'94 Kaplan said. \'93We\'92ll take care of you; we hope you\'92ll take care of us.\'94 What started as referrals to legitimate abortion providers changed to personalized service when some members of Jane learned to safely do the abortions themselves. Between the late 1960s and 1973, the year that the Supreme Court decided Roe v. Wade, Jane had arranged or performed over 11,000 abortions. \'93Our culture is always searching for heroes,\'94 said Kaplan. \'93But you don\'92t have to be a hero to do extraordinary things. Jane was just ordinary people working together \'97 and look what we could accomplish, which is amazing, right?\'94 Even after several members were caught and arrested, the group continued to provide abortions for women too poor to travel to states where abortion had been legalized. \'93I prayed a lot. I didn\'92t want to go to jail,\'94 said 80-year-old Marie Learner, who allowed the Janes to perform abortions at her apartment. \'93Some of us had little children. Some were the sole breadwinners in their home,\'94 Learner said. \'93It was fearlessness in the face of overwhelming odds.\'94 \AppleTypeServices Having an abortion like it\'92s 1965 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 The story of Jane has been immortalized in Kaplan\'92s book, numerous print articles, a 2022 movie, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7461272/"}}{\fldrslt \'93Call Jane,}}\'94 starring Elizabeth Banks and Sigourney Weaver, and a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pRbquE2BAkQ"}}{\fldrslt documentary on HBO}} (which, like CNN, is owned by Warner Bros. Discovery). Today the historical tale of Jane has taken on a new significance. After the 2022 Supreme Court {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/06/24/politics/dobbs-mississippi-supreme-court-abortion-roe-wade"}}{\fldrslt reversal of Roe v. Wade}} and the mid-term takeover of the US House of Representatives by Republicans, emboldened conservative lawmakers and judges have acted on their anti-abortion beliefs. Currently {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/11/23/politics/georgia-abortion-ban-supreme-court/index.html"}}{\fldrslt more than a dozen states}} have banned or imposed severe restrictions on abortion. Georgia has banned abortions {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/11/23/politics/georgia-abortion-ban-supreme-court/index.html"}}{\fldrslt after six weeks}}, even though women are typically unaware they are pregnant at that stage. In mid-April, Florida Governor Ron DeSantis {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2023/04/13/politics/florida-abortion-ban/index.html"}}{\fldrslt signed a bill that would ban most abortions after six weeks.}} It won\'92t go into effect until the state Supreme Court overturns its previous precedent on abortion. Several other states are considering similar legislation. In other states, judicial battles are underway to protect abortion access. \'93It\'92s a horrific situation right now. People will be harmed, some may even die,\'94 said Booth, who helped birth the Jane movement while in college. \'93Women without family support, without the information they need, may be isolated and either harm themselves looking to end an unwanted pregnancy or will be harmed because they went to an unscrupulous and illegal provider,\'94 said Booth, now 77. \AppleTypeServices Today there is medication abortion \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 A key difference between the 60s and today is medication abortion, which {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.guttmacher.org/article/2022/02/medication-abortion-now-accounts-more-half-all-us-abortions"}}{\fldrslt 54% of people }}in the United States used to end a pregnancy in 2022. Available via prescription and through the mail, use of the drugs is two-fold: A person takes a first pill, mifepristone, to block the hormone needed for a pregnancy to continue. 
\f1 \AppleTypeServices \uc0\u8239 
\f0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 A day or two later, the patient takes a second drug, misoprostol, which causes the uterus to contract, creating the cramping and bleeding of labor. In early April a Texas judge, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2023/03/15/politics/matthew-kacsmaryk-texas-judge-medication-abortion-lawsuit/index.html"}}{\fldrslt US District Judge Matthew Kacsmaryk}} \'96 a  Trump appointee who has been vocal about his anti-abortion stance \'97 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2023/04/10/politics/texas-abortion-ruling-politics/index.html"}}{\fldrslt suspended }}the US Food and Drug Administration\'92s approval of mifepristone despite 23 years of data showing the drug is safe to use, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2023/03/15/health/abortion-pill-safety-dg/index.html"}}{\fldrslt safer even than penicillin or Viagra.}} On Friday, the Supreme Court froze the ruling and a subsequent decision by the Fifth US Circuit Court of Appeals at the request of the Justice Department and the drug manufacturer. The action allows access to mifepristone in states where it\'92s legal until appeals play out over the months to come. However, 15 states currently restrict access to medication abortion, even by mail. The actions of anti-abortion activists, who have been accused of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2023/03/03/politics/justice-department-texas-judge-shopping/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \'93judge shopping}}\'94 to get the decisions they want, is \'93an unprecedented attack on democracy meant to undermine the will of the vast majority of Americans who want this pill \'97 mifepristone \'97 to remain legal and available,\'94 Heather Booth told CNN. \'93This is a further weaponization of the courts to brazenly advance the end goal of banning abortion entirely,\'94 she added. If women in her day could have had access to medications that could be used safely in their homes, they would not have been forced to risk their lives, said Dorie Barron, thinking back to her own terrifying abortion in a sketchy Chicago motel. \'93I\'92m depressed as hell, watching stupid, indifferent men control and destroy women\'92s lives all over again,\'94 she said. \'93I really fear getting an abortion could soon be like 1965.\'94 \AppleTypeServices Knowledge is power \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Chicago college student Heather Booth had just finished a summer working with civil rights activists in Mississippi when she was asked to help with a different kind of injustice. A girl in another dorm was considering suicide because she was pregnant. Booth, who excelled at both organization and chutzpah, found a local doctor and negotiated an abortion for the girl. Word spread quickly. \'93There were about 100 women a week calling for help, much more than one person could handle,\'94 Booth said. \'93I recruited about 12 other people and began training them how to do the counseling.\'94 Counseling was a key part of the new service. This was a time when people \'93barely spoke about sex, how women\'92s bodies functioned or even how people got pregnant,\'94 Booth said. To help each woman understand what was going to happen to them, Booth quizzed the abortion provider about every aspect of the procedure. \'93What do you do in advance? Will it be painful? How painful? Can you walk afterwards? Do you need someone to be with you to take you home?\'94 The questions continued: \'93What amount of bleeding is expected, and can a woman handle it on their own? If there\'92s a problem is there an urgent number they can call?\'94 Armed with details few if any physicians provided, the counselors at Jane could fully inform each caller about the abortion experience. The group even published a flyer describing the procedure, long before the groundbreaking 1970 book \'93{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.amazon.com/Bodies-Ourselves-Boston-Womens-Collective/dp/1439190666"}}{\fldrslt Our Bodies, Ourselves}}\'94 began to educate women about their sexuality and health. \'93I don\'92t particularly like doctors because I always feel dissatisfied with the experience,\'94 said Marie Learner, who spoke to many of the women who underwent an abortion at her home. \'93But after their abortion at Jane, women told me, \'91Wow, that was the best experience I\'92ve ever had with people helping me with a medical issue.\'92\'94 Eileen Smith, now 73, was one of those women. \'93Jane made you feel like you were part of this bigger picture, like we were all in this together,\'94 she said. \'93They helped me do this illegal thing and then they\'92re calling to make sure I\'92m OK? Wow! \'93For me, it helped battle the feeling that I was a bad person, that \'91What\'92s wrong with me? Why did I get pregnant? I should know better\'92 voice in my head,\'94 said Smith. \'93It was priceless.\'94 \AppleTypeServices Respecting each woman\'92s choice \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Many of the women who joined Jane had never experienced an abortion. Some viewed the work as political, a part of the burgeoning feminist movement. Others considered the service as simply humanitarian health care. All saw the work as an opportunity to respect each woman\'92s choice. \'93I was a stay-at-home mom with four kids,\'94 said Martha Scott, who is now in her 80s. \'93We knew the woman needed to feel as though she was in control of what was happening to her. We were making it happen for her, but it was not about us. It was about her.\'94 Some volunteers, like Dorie Barron, experienced the Jane difference firsthand when she found herself pregnant a few years after her abortion at the hands of the Mafia. \'93It was a 100% total reversal \'97 I had never experienced such kindness,\'94 Barron said. Not only did a Jane hold each woman\'92s hand and explain every step of the process, \'93they gave each of us a giant supply of maternity sanitary pads, and a nice big handful of antibiotics,\'94 she said. \'93And for the next week, I got a phone call every other day to see how I was.\'94 Barron soon began volunteering for Jane by providing pregnancy testing for women in the back of a church in Chicago\'92s Hyde Park. \'93It wasn\'92t just abortion,\'94 Barron explained. \'93We also said, \'91You could consider adoption,\'92 and gave adoption referrals. And if the woman wanted to continue with her pregnancy, we said, \'91Fine, please by all that is holy make sure you get prenatal care, take your vitamins, and eat as best you can.\'92 It was women helping women with whatever they needed.\'94 Most of the women who contacted Jane were unable to support themselves, in unhealthy relationships, or already had children at home, so the service was a way of \'93helping them get back on track,\'94 said Smith, who, like Barron, had begun working for Jane after her abortion. \'93We were telling them \'91This isn\'92t the end of the world. You can continue to leave your boyfriend or your husband or continue to just take care of those kids you have.\'92 We were there to help them get through this,\'94 said Smith, who later became a homecare nurse. Diane Stevens says she came to work for Jane after experiencing an abortion in 1968 at the age of 19. She was living in California at the time, which provided \'93therapeutic abortions\'94 if approved in advance by physicians. \'93I\'92d had a birth control failure, and I was coached by Planned Parenthood on how to do this,\'94 said Stevens, now 74. \'93I had to see two psychiatrists and one doctor and tell them I was not able to go through with the pregnancy because it would a danger to both my physical and mental health. \'93I was admitted to the psychiatric ward, although I didn\'92t really know that \'97 I thought I was just in a hospital bed. But oh no, \'91I was mentally ill,\'92 so that\'92s where they put me,\'94 said Stevens, who later went to nursing school with Smith. \'93Then they wheeled me off for the abortion. I had general anesthesia, was there for two days, and then I was discharged. Isn\'92t that crazy?\'94 Sakinah Ahad Shannon, now 75, was one of the few Black women who volunteered as a counselor at Jane. She joined after accompanying a friend who was charged a mere $50 for her abortion. At that time, Jane\'92s fee was between $1 and $100, based on what the woman could afford to pay, Shannon said. \'93When I walked in, I said, \'91Oh my God, here we go again. It\'92s a room of White women, archangels who are going to save the world,\'92\'94 said Shannon, a social worker and member of the Congress of Racial Equality, an interracial group of non-violent activists who pioneered \'93Freedom Rides\'94 and helped organize the March on Washington in 1963. What she heard and saw at her friend\'92s counseling session was so impressive it \'93changed my life,\'94 Shannon said. She and her family later opened and operated three Chicago abortion clinics for over 25 years, all using the Jane philosophy of communication and respect. \'93It was a profoundly amazing experience for me,\'94 she said. \'93I call the Janes my sisters. The color line didn\'92t matter. We were all taking the same risk.\'94 \AppleTypeServices We can take care of ourselves \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 It wasn\'92t long before the women discovered a \'93doctor\'94 performing abortions for Jane had been lying about his credentials. There was no medical degree \'97 in the HBO documentary, he admitted he had honed his skills by assisting an abortion provider. The group imploded. A number of members quit in horror and dismay. For the women who stayed, it was an epiphany, said Martha Scott. Like her, several of the Janes had been assisting this fake doctor for years, learning the procedures step by step. \'93You\'92d learn how to insert a speculum, then how to swap out the vagina with an antiseptic, then how to give numbing shots around the cervix and then how to dilate the cervix. You learned and mastered each step before you moved on to the next,\'94 said Laura Kaplan, who chronicled the procedure in her book. By now, several of the Janes were quite experienced and willing to do the work. Why not perform the abortions themselves? \'93Clearly, this was an intense responsibility,\'94 said Judith Acana, a 27-year-old high school teacher who joined Jane in 1970. She started her training by helping \'93long terms,\'94 women who were four or five months along in the pregnancy. \'93Remember, abortion was illegal (in Illinois) so it could take weeks for a woman to find help,\'94 said Arcana, now 80. \'93Frequently women who wanted an abortion at 8 or 10 weeks wound up being 16 or 18 weeks or more by the time they found Jane.\'94 The miscarriage could happen quickly, but it rarely did, she said. It usually took anywhere from one to two days. \'93Women who had no one to help them would come back when contractions started,\'94 Arcana said. \'93One of my strongest memories is of a teenage girl who had an appointment to have her miscarriage on my living room floor.\'94 The group also paid two Janes to live in an apartment and be on call 24/7 to assist women who had no one to help them miscarry at home, said Arcana, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.juditharcana.com/"}}{\fldrslt a lifelong educator, author and poet}}. \'93But many women took care of it on their own, in very amazing and impressive and powerful ways,\'94 she said. Any woman who had concerns or questions while miscarrying alone could always call Jane for advice any time of the day or night. \'93People would call in a panic: \'91The bleeding won\'92t stop,\'92\'94 Smith recalled. \'93I would tell them, \'91Get some ice, put it on your stomach, elevate your legs, relax.\'92 And they would say \'91Oh my gosh, thank you!\'92 because they were so scared.\'94 For women who were in their first trimester, Jane offered traditional D&C abortions \'97 the same dilation and
