\f1 \AppleTypeServices \uc0\u8239 
\f0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 used by hospitals then and today, said Scott, who performed many of the abortions for Jane. Later the group used vacuum aspiration, which was over in a mere five to 10 minutes. \'93Vacuum aspiration was much easier to do, and I think it\'92s less difficult for the woman,\'94 Scott said. \'93Abortion is exactly like any other medical procedure. It\'92s the decision that\'92s an issue \'97 the doing is very straightforward. This was something a competent, trained person could do.\'94 \AppleTypeServices Busted, but not broken \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 It was May 3, 1972. Judith Arcana was the driver that day, responsible for relocating women waiting at what was called \'93the front\'94 to a separate apartment or house where the abortions were done, known as \'93the place.\'94 On this day, a Wednesday, the \'93place\'94 was a South Shore high-rise apartment. Arcana was escorting a woman who had completed her abortion when they were stopped by police at the elevator. \'93They asked us, \'91Which apartment did you come out of?\'92 And the poor woman burst into tears and blurted out the apartment number,\'94 Arcana said. \'93They took me downstairs, put cuffs on me and hooked me to a steel hook inside of the police van.\'94 Inside the apartment on the 11th floor, Martha Scott said she was setting up the bedroom for the next abortion when she heard a knock at the door, followed by screaming: \'93You can\'92t come in!\'94 \'93I shut the bedroom door and locked it,\'94 Scott said, then hid the instruments and sat on the bed to wait. It wasn\'92t long until a cop kicked the door in and made her join the other women in the living room. \'93We tell this joke about how the cops came in, saw all these women and said, \'91Where\'92s the abortionist?\'92 You know, assuming that it would be a man,\'94 Scott said. By day\'92s end, seven members of Jane were behind bars: Martha Scott, Diane Stevens, Judy Arcana, Jeanne Galatzer-Levy, Abby Pariser, Sheila Smith and Madeleine Schwenk. Suddenly what had been an underground effort for years was front page headlines. \'93Had we not gotten arrested, I think no one would ever have known about Jane other than the women we served,\'94 Scott said. An emergency meeting of Jane was called. The turnout was massive \'97 even women who had not been active in months showed up, anxious to know the extent of the police probe, according to the women with whom CNN spoke. Despite widespread fear and worry, the group immediately began making alternate plans for women scheduled for abortions at Jane in the next few days to weeks. The group even paid for transportation to other cities where abortion had already been legalized, they said. News reports over the next few days gave further details of the bust: There was no widespread investigation by the police. It was a single incident, triggered by a call from a sister-in-law who was upset with her relative\'92s decision to have an abortion, they said. \'93It wasn\'92t long after I was arrested that I came back and worked for quite a few months,\'94 said Scott, one of the few fully trained to do abortions. \'93I like to think I was a good soldier,\'94 Scott said. \'93I like to think what did made a difference not only to a whole bunch of people, but also to ourselves. It gave us a sense of empowerment that comes when you do something that is hard to do and also right.\'94 As paranoia eased, women began to come back to work at Jane, determined to carry on. \'93After the bust, we had a meeting and were told \'91Everybody needs to start assisting and learn how to do abortions.\'92 I was like, \'91Whoa, whoa, whoa!\'92\'94 said Eileen Smith, who had not been arrested. \'93But you felt like you really didn\'92t have much of a choice. We had to keep the service running.\'94 \AppleTypeServices Rescued by \'91Jane Roe\'92 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 The preliminary hearing for the arrested seven was in August. Several of the women in the apartment waiting for abortions the day of the arrest suddenly developed amnesia and refused to testify. According to Kaplan\'92s book, one of the women later said, \'93The cops tried to push me around, but f**k them. I wasn\'92t going to tell on you.\'94 It didn\'92t matter. Each Jane was charged with 11 counts of abortion and conspiracy to commit abortion, with a possible sentence of up to 110 years in prison. As they waited for trial, the lawyer for the seven, Jo-Anne Wolfson, adopted delaying tactics, Kaplan said. A case representing a Texas woman, cited as \'93Jane Roe\'94 to protect her privacy, was being considered by the US Supreme Court. If the Court ruled in Roe\'92s favor, the case against the Jane\'92s might be thrown out. That\'92s exactly what happened. On March 9, 1973, three months after the Supreme Court had legalized abortion in the US, the case against the seven women was dropped and their arrest records were expunged. Later that spring, a majority of Janes, burned out by the intensity of the work over the last few years, voted to close shop. An end of Jane party was held on May 20. According to Kaplan\'92s book, the invitation read: \'93You are cordially invited to attend The First, Last and Only Curette Caper; the Grand Finale of the Abortion Counseling Service. RSVP: Call Jane.\'94 \AppleTypeServices Epilogue \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Today, most of the surviving members of Jane are in their 70s and 80s, shocked but somehow not surprised by the actions of abortion opponents. \'93This is a country of ill-educated politicos who know nothing about women\'92s bodies, nor do they care,\'94 said Dorie Barron. \'93It will take generations to even begin to undo the devastating harm to women\'92s rights.\'94 In the meantime, women should research all available options, keep that information confidential, seek support from groups working for abortion rights, and \'93share your education with as many women as you can,\'94 Barron added. As more and more reproductive freedoms have been rolled back over the past year, many of the Janes are angry and fearful for the future. \'93This is about the most intimate decision of our lives \'97 when, whether and with whom we have a child. Everyone should have the ability to make decisions about our own lives, bodies, and futures without political interference,\'94 said Heather Booth, who has spent her life after leaving Jane fighting for civil and women\'92s rights. \'93We need to organize, raise our voices and our votes, and overturn this attack on our freedom and our lives. I have seen that when we take action and organize we can change the world.\'94\
\AppleTypeServices \
