Article: 49\
News_Outlet: CNN\
Title: Texas woman almost dies because she couldn\'92t get an abortion\
Author: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/profiles/elizabeth-cohen"}}{\fldrslt Elizabeth Cohen}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/profiles/john-bonifield"}}{\fldrslt John Bonifield}}\
Publication_Date: Updated 7:17 AM EDT, Tue June 20, 2023\
Article_Content: CNN \'a0\'97\'a0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Another woman has come forward with the harrowing details of how the Supreme Court\'92s decision four months ago to overturn Roe v. Wade put her life in danger. CNN has told the stories of several women \'96 including one from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/07/20/health/doctors-weigh-litigation-miscarriage-care/index.html"}}{\fldrslt Houston}}, one from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/09/09/health/abortion-restrictions-texas/index.html"}}{\fldrslt central Texas}} and one from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/09/22/health/ohio-abortion-patient-doctor/index.html"}}{\fldrslt Cleveland}} \'96 and what they had to do to obtain medically necessary abortions.\AppleTypeServices  \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Now, a woman from Austin, Texas, has come forward because she nearly died when she couldn\'92t get a timely {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/specials/us/abortion-reproductive-rights"}}{\fldrslt abortion}}. This is her story. \AppleTypeServices The loss of a \'91miracle\'92 baby \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Amanda Eid and Josh Zurawski, both now 35, met in 1991 at Aldersgate Academy preschool in Fort Wayne, Indiana, and dated in high school. \'93Josh always tells me he\'92s been in love with me since we were 4 years old,\'94 Amanda said. Three years ago, they married in Austin, Texas, where they both work in high-tech jobs. They tried to have a family but failed. Amanda had fertility treatments for a year and a half and finally became pregnant. \'93Very excited to share that Baby Zurawski is expected in late January,\'94 Amanda shared on Instagram in July. The post included a picture of her and her husband in \'93Mama\'94 and \'93Dad\'94 hats, Amanda holding a strip of ultrasound photos of their baby girl. \'93The fact that we were pregnant at all was a miracle, and we were beside ourselves with happiness,\'94 she said. But then, 18 weeks \'96 just four months \'96 into her pregnancy, Amanda\'92s water broke. The amniotic fluid that her baby depended upon was leaking out. She says her doctor told her the baby would not survive. \'93We found out that we were going to lose our baby,\'94 Amanda said. \'93My cervix was dilating fully 22 weeks prematurely, and I was inevitably going to miscarry.\'94 She and Josh begged the doctor to see if there was any way to save the baby. \'93I just kept asking, \'91isn\'92t there anything we can do?\'92 And the answer was \'91no,\'92 \'94 Amanda said. \AppleTypeServices Texas anti-abortion laws \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 When a woman\'92s water breaks, she\'92s at high risk for a life-threatening infection. While Amanda and Josh\'92s baby \'96 they named her Willow \'96 was sure to die, she still had a heartbeat, and so doctors said that under Texas law, they were unable to terminate the pregnancy. \'93My doctor said, \'91Well, right now we just have to wait, because we can\'92t induce labor, even though you\'92re 100% for sure going to lose your baby,\'92 \'94 Amanda said. \'93[The doctors] were unable to do their own jobs because of the way that the laws are written in Texas.\'94 Texas{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://capitol.texas.gov/BillLookup/Text.aspx?LegSess=87R&Bill=HB1280"}}{\fldrslt  law}} allows for abortion if the mother \'93has a life-threatening physical condition aggravated, caused by, or arising from a pregnancy that places the female at risk of death or poses a serious risk of substantial impairment of a major bodily function.\'94 But Texas lawmakers haven\'92t spelled out exactly what that means, and a doctor found to be in violation of the law can face loss of their medical license and a possible life sentence in prison. \'93They\'92re extremely vague,\'94 said Katie Keith, director of the Health Policy and Law Initiative at Georgetown University Law Center. \'93They don\'92t spell out exactly the situations when an abortion can be provided.\'94 In September, CNN reached out to 28 Texas legislators who sponsored anti-abortion legislation, asking them for their response to CNN stories about the woman in Houston and the woman in central Texas. Only one legislator responded. \'93Like any other law, there are unintended consequences. We do not want to see any unintended consequences; if we do, it is our responsibility as legislators to fix those flaws,\'94 wrote state Sen. Eddie Lucio, who will be leaving the Senate at the end of the year. The Zurawskis participated in an {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aiHbyI0Coe0"}}{\fldrslt ad}} for Beto O\'92Rourke\'92s unsuccessful Texas gubernatorial campaign. \AppleTypeServices Going downhill very fast \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 After her water broke, Amanda\'92s doctors sent her home and told her to watch for signs of infection, and that only when she was \'93considered sick enough that my life was at risk\'94 would they terminate the pregnancy, Amanda said. \'93My doctor said it could take hours, it could take days, it could take weeks,\'94 she remembers. Once they heard \'93hours,\'94 they decided there was no time to travel to another state for an abortion. \'93The nearest \'91sanctuary\'92 state is at least an eight-hour drive,\'94 Amanda wrote in an online essay on {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wearethemeteor.com/texas-abortion-ban-stopped-doctors-helping-woman-miscarrying/"}}{\fldrslt The Meteor}}. \'93Developing sepsis \'96 which can kill quickly \'96 in a car in the middle of the West Texas desert, or 30,000 feet above the ground, is a death sentence.\'94 So they waited it out in Texas. On August 26, three days after her water broke, Amanda found herself shivering in the Texas heat. \'93We were having a heat wave, I think it was 105 degrees that day, and I was freezing cold, and I was shaking, my teeth were chattering. I was trying to tell Josh that I didn\'92t feel good, and my teeth were chattering so hard that I could not even get the sentence out,\'94 she said. Josh was shocked by his wife\'92s condition. \'93To see in a matter of maybe five minutes, for her to go from a normal temperature to the condition she was in was really, really scary,\'94 he said. \'93Very quickly, she went downhill very, very fast. She was in a state I\'92ve never seen her in.\'94 Josh rushed his wife to the hospital. Her temperature was 102 degrees. She was too weak to walk on her own. Her temperature went up to 103 degrees. Finally, Amanda was sick enough that the doctors felt legally safe to terminate the pregnancy, she said. \AppleTypeServices \'91I was really scared I was going to lose her\'92 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 But Amanda was so sick that antibiotics wouldn\'92t stop the bacterial infection raging through her body. A blood transfusion didn\'92t cure her, either. About 12 hours after her pregnancy was terminated, doctors and nurses flooded her room. \'93There\'92s a lot of commotion, and I said, \'91what\'92s going on?\'92 and they said, \'91we\'92re moving you to the ICU,\'92 and I said, \'91why?\'92 and they said, \'91you\'92re developing symptoms of sepsis,\'92 \'94 she said. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cdc.gov/sepsis/what-is-sepsis.html"}}{\fldrslt Sepsis}}, the body\'92s extreme response to an infection, is a life-threatening medical emergency. Amanda\'92s blood pressure plummeted. Her platelets dropped. She doesn\'92t remember much from that time. But Josh does. \'93It was really scary to see Amanda crash,\'94 he said. \'93I was really scared I was going to lose her.\'94 Family members flew in from across the country because they feared it would be the last time they would see Amanda. Doctors inserted an intravenous line near her heart to deliver antibiotics and medication to stabilize her blood pressure. Finally, Amanda turned the corner and survived. \AppleTypeServices \'91These barbaric laws\'92 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 But her medical ordeal isn\'92t over. Amanda\'92s uterus suffered scarring from the infection, and she may not be able to have more children. She had a surgery recently to fix the scarring, but it\'92s unclear whether it will be successful. That leaves the Zurawskis scared \'96 and furious that they might never have a family because of a Texas law. \'93[This] didn\'92t have to happen,\'94 Amanda said. \'93That\'92s what\'92s so infuriating about all of this, is that we didn\'92t have to \'96 we shouldn\'92t have had to \'96 go through all of this trauma.\'94 The Zurawskis say the politicians who voted for the anti-abortion law call themselves \'93pro-life\'94 \'96 but they don\'92t see it that way. \'93Amanda almost died. That\'92s not pro-life. Amanda will have challenges in the future having more kids. That\'92s not pro-life,\'94 Josh said. \'93Nothing about [this] feels pro-life,\'94 his wife added. In many ways, Amanda feels fortunate. She wonders whether she\'92d be alive today if it weren\'92t for her husband, who rushed her to the hospital and made sure she got the best care possible. And they have good jobs with good health insurance and they live in a big city with high quality health care. \'93All of these things I had going for me, and still, this was the outcome,\'94 she said. She and Josh worry about women in rural areas, or poor women, or young, single mothers in states like Texas. What would happen to them, considering what happened to Amanda? \'93These barbaric laws prevented her from getting any amount of health care when she needed it, until it was at a life-threatening moment,\'94 Josh said.\
