Title:The language we use to talk about pregnancy and abortion is changing. But not everyone welcomes the shift\
Author: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/profiles/harmeet-kaur"}}{\fldrslt Harmeet Kaur}}\
Publication_Date:  Published 6:01 AM EDT, Sun September 4, 2022\
Article_Content: CNN \'a0\'97\'a0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 From {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.acog.org/clinical-information/policy-and-position-statements/statements-of-policy/2022/inclusive-language"}}{\fldrslt patient waiting rooms}} to the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.aclu.org/news/reproductive-freedom/why-we-use-inclusive-language-to-talk-about-abortion"}}{\fldrslt halls of Congress}}, the language being used to talk about reproduction is shifting. Across the US, mainstream institutions such as the American Civil Liberties Union, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention and CNN are increasingly opting for gender-neutral terms such as \'93pregnant people,\'94 \'93people who get abortions\'94 and \'93birthing parent\'94 in favor of \'93women\'94 when referencing pregnancy, fertility and abortion. These shifts in terminology signal an effort to be inclusive of transgender and nonbinary people who can also get pregnant. But the changes have also prompted pushback \'96 not just from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G0PmSWfN_WE&ab_channel=CNN"}}{\fldrslt Republican politicians}} who are openly {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/04/22/politics/republicans-anti-lgbtq-legislation/index.html"}}{\fldrslt hostile to LGBTQ people}} but also from some {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2020/06/10/health/gender-identity-explainer-wellness/index.html"}}{\fldrslt cisgender}} women (women whose gender identity conforms with the sex they were assigned at birth) who consider themselves LGBTQ allies and who support abortion rights. \'93We\'92re not just talking about the same people that we were before. We\'92re broadening the scope,\'94 said Kristen Syrett, an associate professor of linguistics at Rutgers University. \'93And I think that\'92s where people get more uncomfortable because it\'92s so different from the way we\'92ve been thinking of reproductive rights and pregnancy for a long time.\'94 Debates about language can seem arbitrary at a time when so many {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/08/25/politics/where-abortion-banned-states-court-legal-challenges/index.html"}}{\fldrslt no longer have access to abortion services}} in their home state. But at the crux of these debates are questions about who is targeted by restrictive laws and policies, who is affected and who is included in the conversation. \AppleTypeServices Advocates say inclusive terms make room for everyone affected \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Using inclusive language to talk about abortion recognizes that not only cis women can get pregnant, said Gillian Branstetter, a communications strategist at the ACLU\'92s Women\'92s Rights Project and LGBTQ & HIV Project. Some trans men and nonbinary people can also get pregnant, as can cis girls and trans boys. This is also true in the opposite: Not all women are able to get pregnant. Some cis women struggle with fertility, while trans women lack uteruses. Opting for gender-neutral terms such as \'93people\'94 or \'93patients\'94 allows for these nuances in a way that just saying \'93women\'94 does not. There\'92s scant data on how many trans and nonbinary people get pregnant and receive abortions given that medical systems in the US track them as female. A {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.eurekalert.org/news-releases/719868"}}{\fldrslt 2019 study from Rutgers University}} suggests that up to 30% of trans men experience unplanned pregnancies, and a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2590151620300022?via%3Dihub#bi0005"}}{\fldrslt 2020 study from researchers at the Guttmacher Institute and Planned Parenthood}} estimated between 462 and 530 trans and nonbinary people received abortions in 2017 (the CDC {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/69/ss/ss6907a1.htm"}}{\fldrslt reports}} that approximately 609,000 total abortions were performed that year). As {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2022/06/07/about-5-of-young-adults-in-the-u-s-say-their-gender-is-different-from-their-sex-assigned-at-birth/"}}{\fldrslt more adults identify as trans or nonbinary}}, experts say that such estimates are likely undercounted. Still, those numbers pale in comparison to the numbers of cis women who access reproductive health care \'96 a point often made by critics of more inclusive terms. Branstetter acknowledged this reality, noting that \'9399% of people who are going to become pregnant or are in need of birth control or an abortion are women.\'94 But it\'92s necessary to make room for trans and nonbinary people precisely because of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/08/27/us/transgender-nonbinary-abortion-reproductive-care-reaj/index.html"}}{\fldrslt significant barriers}} they face in receiving reproductive care, she added. \'93It\'92s important to remember that transgender people do not have the privilege of pretending we do not exist.\'94 \AppleTypeServices Some feel gender-neutral terms erase the role of sexism \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Others are concerned that forgoing the term \'93women\'94 obscures what they see as the driving force behind attacks on abortion rights: Misogyny. Carrie Baker, professor of the study of women and gender at Smith College, considers gender-neutral terms such as \'93pregnant people\'94 to be inaccurate and imprecise. In theory, she said, \'93people\'94 also includes cisgender men, whose bodies are not affected by abortion restrictions. Baker said she recognizes the importance of being inclusive, and tries to reference in her writing when possible the various groups who are affected by abortion restrictions. But because she sees cisgender women as the primary targets of abortion bans, she said she makes it a point to emphasize women. Not doing so, Baker said, erases the sexism underlying laws that seek to exert control over women\'92s bodies. \'93\'91Pregnant people\'92 doesn\'92t say who we\'92re talking about. It makes (pregnancy) sound like it\'92s a gender-neutral phenomenon or a sex-neutral phenomenon,\'94 she added. \'93I believe that bans on abortion are motivated by sex discrimination and by bias against women and cisgender women, or just femininity.\'94 As some abortion rights supporters now look to the{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://19thnews.org/2022/08/young-equal-rights-amendment-activists-abortion-rights/"}}{\fldrslt  Equal Rights Amendment}} to establish a constitutional right to abortion, Baker said being explicit about the role of sexism in abortion restrictions is necessary to challenge such laws. Doing that effectively, in her view, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://msmagazine.com/2022/06/23/women-abortion-bans-inclusive-language-pregnant-people/"}}{\fldrslt means naming women}}. \'93I think we need to talk about that or we, in essence, do what the right does, which is trying to erase the significance of the discriminatory impact of abortion bans,\'94 Baker said. Some have gone as far as to suggest that women as a class are being erased. Earlier this year, The New York Times opinion columnist {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2022/07/03/opinion/the-far-right-and-far-left-agree-on-one-thing-women-dont-count.html"}}{\fldrslt Pamela Paul }}decried the use of terms such as \'93pregnant people\'94 in a piece, writing that \'93This isn\'92t just a semantic issue; it\'92s also a question of moral harm, an affront to our very sense of ourselves.\'94 The Atlantic\'92s {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/05/abortion-rights-debate-women-gender-neutral-language/629863/"}}{\fldrslt Helen Lewis}} accused the left of \'93declaring a war on saying \'91women.\'92\'94 \'93By substituting people for women, we lose the ability to speak of women as a class. We dismantle them into pieces, into functions, into commodities,\'94 she argued. Syrett, the Rutgers University linguist, understands where these anxieties are coming from, but encourages people to reflect on what they\'92re signaling with their word choices. \'93It seems natural for some individuals to (feel) like this is taking away something or maybe it\'92s not honoring a part of what they\'92ve associated with womanhood for so long,\'94 she said. \'93It\'92s an opportunity for everyone, regardless of their own stance with respect to reproductive issues or their own experience, to take a step back and ask what it means to talk about \'91women\'92 versus \'91females\'92 versus \'91people with the ability to reproduce.\'92\'94 \AppleTypeServices Others say the debate presents a false dichotomy \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 For the ACLU\'92s Branstetter, claims that women are being erased are overblown. Progressive organizations are opting for terms such as \'93pregnant people\'94 in their own public messaging campaigns, but no one is forcing women to stop describing themselves as such, she said. Additionally, the word \'93women\'94 continues to be centered in many national conversations about abortion \'96 from the Women\'92s Health Protection Act that sought to codify Roe v. Wade to the Supreme Court ruling Dobbs v. Jackson Women\'92s Health Organization that overturned it. \'93I think that the demise of the word \'91woman\'92 is greatly exaggerated,\'94 Branstetter said. \'93And I don\'92t think that there\'92s any harm in making space for the many people who do need this care who are not women.\'94 Advocates of more inclusive terms also feel that such debates present a false dichotomy. Oliver Hall, trans health director for the Kentucky Health Justice Network, said critics of terms such as \'93pregnant people\'94 are missing the ways that trans and nonbinary people are also hurt by misogyny. Recognizing what drives abortion restrictions and making space for trans and nonbinary people aren\'92t mutually exclusive, they added. \'93I think people feel like not just saying \'91women\'92 means that we can\'92t talk about the role that misogyny plays in these laws,\'94 Hall said. \'93But I think that also does a disservice to trans people who are also affected not just by those laws, but by misogyny as a whole.\'94 Including trans and nonbinary people in the fight for abortion rights doesn\'92t mean taking away something from cisgender women, Hall said. Rather, a more inclusive coalition has the potential to strengthen the abortion rights movement. At the heart of abortion bans is a desire to uphold traditional gender roles, Branstetter said, comparing them to attempts to ban {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2022/04/21/health/gender-affirming-care/index.html"}}{\fldrslt gender-affirming care}}. \'93What the effort to ban abortion and the effort to erase transgender people from public life have in common is the enforcement of a very strict gender binary based on the exploitation of reproductive labor,\'94 she said. \'93That is a more complicated story to tell than \'91They\'92re doing it because they hate women.\'92 But it\'92s a truer one.\'94\AppleTypeServices \
